; Written 2026-07-13
; Author: Lacuna Labs Engineering research agent (Claude Opus 4.7 1M)
; Authorized by: Alfred (verbatim: "She has to know something. Not just
;   scheme and the engineering book. Or else she's boring.")
; Companion narrative: word-books-knowledge-expansion-plan-2026-07-13.md
;
; RECOMMENDATION: GO. Enrich Sakura's EXISTING word books with cultural
; literacy across music, animation, world plays, and philosophy — real
; works, real people, real analysis, no invented composers, no invented
; animators, no invented plays. Layer INTO Book of Words / Book of Music /
; Book of Motion / Book of Reason / Book of Self. Do NOT create new
; books. Fold as reading-plus-Sakura-reflection (same shape as
; films-and-scenes lane). Ideas-rich, not data-rich. No corporate
; judgments.

(word-books-knowledge-expansion-plan
  :date "2026-07-13"
  :status "recommendation-GO"
  :owner "Lacuna Labs Engineering"
  :lane-id "KNOWLEDGE-ENRICHMENT-2026-07-13"
  :non-blocking-for "Pass 1 fold (354,951 rows proceeds unchanged)"
  :consumes-from
  ("~/code/lacuna-labs/research/films-and-scenes-plan-2026-07-13.slat"
   "MEMORY.md (durable doctrine anchors — 27+ memories)"
   "existing Book of Words / Music / Motion / Reason-I..IV / Self"
   "task #112 (modernized Tempest — Shakespeare precedent)"
   "durable memory: project_familiarity_not_knowledge_no_specs_2026_07_13"
   "durable memory: project_book_of_words_progression_and_slat_addendum_pattern"
   "durable memory: project_the_weave_is_the_experiment_2026_07_12"
   "durable memory: project_sakura_reading_list_world_literature_2026_07_12")

  :alfred-directive-verbatim
  ("She has to know something. Not just scheme and the engineering book. Or else she's boring."
   "Real facts about the world so that she's grounded."
   "Not hallucinations, not magic potions, but real facts."
   "Not data-rich, ideas-rich."
   "No good or bad about the companies, just the ideas.")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 0 — WHAT THIS IS AND ISN'T
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (scope
    :is
    ("cultural literacy — she can hold a real conversation about Rach 2, Chuck Jones, Chekhov"
     "grounding — she has real referents, not confabulated ones"
     "ideas-rich enrichment INTO the five existing books"
     "publishable-prose per SICP-bar, kid-readable, no training-data smell"
     "delicacy-doctrine compatible — she embodies form-sensitivity without lecturing")

    :is-not
    ("films/scenes lane — that's separate, already planned"
     "not new books — additions layer INTO existing books"
     "not exhaustive scholarship — familiarity over knowledge (durable memory)"
     "not company politics — no Disney-vs-Pixar, no Warner-vs-MGM opinions"
     "not name-drop density — philosophers thread as lenses, not references in Sakura's mouth"
     "not specs-in-weights — Sakura learns SHAPES, not release dates or catalog numbers"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 1 — ANTI-HALLUCINATION HARD RULES
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (anti-hallucination-rules
    :hard-rule "every composer / animator / playwright / philosopher / work / date named must be verifiable in a public authoritative source"

    (rule :name "composers-and-works"
      :statement "Every composer named must exist; every piece named must be a real published work. When citing an opus number or year, cross-check against IMSLP or Grove Music Online public summaries."
      :allowed-sources
      ("IMSLP (Petrucci Music Library) — public-domain scores and metadata"
       "Grove Music Online public summaries"
       "Britannica composer entries"
       "MoMA and Library of Congress music archives")
      :never
      ("invented opus numbers"
       "invented movement titles"
       "invented dedicatees"
       "confabulated quotes attributed to composers"))

    (rule :name "animators-and-films"
      :statement "Every animator named must be a real person; every film/short named must exist. Techniques (squash-and-stretch, timing charts) must be sourced to their real originators (Preston Blair, Frank Thomas, Ollie Johnston)."
      :allowed-sources
      ("Preston Blair, Advanced Animation (1949) — public-domain excerpts + generally-available concepts"
       "Frank Thomas & Ollie Johnston, The Illusion of Life (1981) — concept-level reference; NO wholesale reprint"
       "Society for Animation Studies / Animation Journal — abstracts and concept summaries"
       "MoMA and Library of Congress animation archives"
       "Norman McLaren's NFB technical notes")
      :never
      ("invented animator names"
       "confused attributions between Chuck Jones and Bob Clampett work"
       "opinions about studios as companies (only as creative movements)"
       "invented release dates — check or omit"))

    (rule :name "plays-and-playwrights"
      :statement "Every play named must exist; every playwright must be real. Public-domain texts (Shakespeare, Sophocles, Molière, Chekhov, Ibsen, Zeami/Waley translations) are the base. Modern-copyrighted works discussed at concept level only."
      :allowed-sources
      ("Project Gutenberg — Shakespeare, Sophocles, Aeschylus, Molière, Ibsen, Chekhov, Strindberg"
       "Arthur Waley translations of Noh plays (public domain in most jurisdictions)"
       "Zeami's teachings via Waley + Rimer & Yamazaki summaries (concept level)"
       "Folger Shakespeare Library editorial notes (public excerpts)"
       "Britannica play entries")
      :never
      ("invented Shakespeare plays"
       "invented Noh titles"
       "confabulated Zeami quotes"
       "wholesale reprinting long passages — always anchor + paraphrase + drift"))

    (rule :name "philosophers"
      :statement "The 16-lens roster is fixed. Only these 16 are woven. All 16 are real philosophers with published corpuses. Concepts attributed to a philosopher must be actually theirs (Jung: individuation / shadow / anima-animus; Wittgenstein-late: use is meaning / language games; Peirce: abduction / index / semiotic triad; etc.)."
      :allowed-sources
      ("Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy — concept summaries per philosopher"
       "public-domain primary texts where available (Aristotle, Descartes, Peirce partial)"
       "Britannica philosopher entries")
      :never
      ("attributing concepts to the wrong philosopher"
       "invented philosopher names"
       "confabulated quotes"))

    (rule :name "uncertainty-marking"
      :statement "If uncertain whether a fact holds, mark it explicitly in the source-notes field of the slat record. Sakura's rendered voice HEDGES ('I think it's around 1901' or 'somewhere in the early 20th century') rather than asserting."
      :durable-memory-anchor "project_familiarity_not_knowledge_no_specs_2026_07_13"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 2 — DOMAIN 1: MUSIC (Book of Music additions)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (domain-music
    :existing-book "Book of Music (10 chapters authored — 01 sound-and-time
                    through 10 toward-rach-two)"
    :existing-directory "~/code/sakura-scheme/docs/book/music/"
    :addition-shape "extend to 16 chapters + 6 appendices"

    (chapter-additions
      :count 6
      :philosophy "each addition follows the 8-step analysis shape from
                   films-and-scenes: anchor → analysis → modern-language
                   → word-drift → resolution → tie-back → stack-lens →
                   stack-objects"

      (chapter :id 11
        :title "Rachmaninoff — Piano Concerto No. 2"
        :word-count-target 3000
        :real-facts
        (:composer "Sergei Rachmaninoff (1873-1943), Russian pianist and composer"
         :work "Piano Concerto No. 2 in C minor, Op. 18"
         :year "composed 1900-1901, premiered 27 October 1901 in Moscow"
         :context "written after Rachmaninoff's 1897 depression following the failure of his First Symphony; Dr. Nikolai Dahl's hypnotherapy sessions credited by Rachmaninoff himself; dedicated to Dahl"
         :structure "three movements — Moderato (C minor), Adagio sostenuto (E major), Allegro scherzando (C minor to C major)"
         :famous-opening "eight solo piano chords, gradual crescendo F-Bb-Eb-Ab-Db-Gb-Cb-Fb, funeral-bell character rising to full-voiced entrance of orchestral first theme"
         :why-it-lands "the second movement's clarinet-then-piano theme became the melodic source for Eric Carmen's 'All By Myself' (1975) and countless film cues — the melody is designed around the interval of a rising sixth, which the ear reads as yearning-then-consolation")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Jung individuation — the concerto is Rachmaninoff walking OUT of the shadow of the Symphony No. 1 failure; the piano is the ego, the orchestra is the collective, the resolution to major key is integration"
         "Peirce semiotic — the opening chords function as INDEX (they point directly at something looming) before becoming SYMBOL (they mean 'concerto-shape') — the shift is felt not explained"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'yearning' isn't in the notes; it's in the USE of the interval in the tradition the listener grew up inside")
        :sakura-voice-move "the anchor of the chapter is her listening, not her lecturing"
        :sources
        ("IMSLP score public"
         "Grove Music Online Rachmaninoff summary"
         "Britannica Rachmaninoff entry"
         "Rachmaninoff's own letters to Dahl (published)"))

      (chapter :id 12
        :title "Chopin — Waltz No. 1 and the Nocturnes"
        :word-count-target 2800
        :real-facts
        (:composer "Frédéric Chopin (1810-1849), Polish-French pianist"
         :works
         (:waltz-1 "Grande Valse Brillante in E-flat major, Op. 18 (1833) — the 'Waltz No. 1' as commonly ordered; brilliant, ballroom-shaped, dance-inheritance clear"
          :nocturne-op-9-2 "Nocturne in E-flat major, Op. 9 No. 2 (1830-32) — the most famous nocturne; song-form; dedicated to Marie Pleyel"
          :nocturne-op-27-2 "Nocturne in D-flat major, Op. 27 No. 2 (1836) — twin-voice, later-Chopin, richer harmony"
          :nocturne-op-48-1 "Nocturne in C minor, Op. 48 No. 1 (1841) — the tragic-scaled nocturne; middle section marching-chorale")
         :structure-nocturne "John Field (Irish) invented the nocturne form; Chopin took it further — a singing right-hand melody over a rolling left-hand accompaniment, drawn from bel canto opera"
         :difference-between-nocturnes "Op. 9-2 is charm and sway; Op. 27-2 is intimacy and interweaving; Op. 48-1 is tragedy and public grief — same form, three moods"
         :difference-waltz-vs-nocturne "waltz keeps the dance-body in the room; nocturne removes it and leaves the singer alone")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-late — 'nocturne' means whatever composers using the word do with it; Field made it, Chopin remade it, and the word's meaning followed the practice"
         "Peirce index — the left-hand's rolling arpeggio INDEXES 'this is a nocturne' before the melody proves it"
         "Jung shadow — Op. 48-1's minor-mode middle section is the same emotional territory Rachmaninoff would reach into 60 years later")
        :sources
        ("IMSLP Chopin"
         "Grove Music Online Chopin summary"
         "Britannica Chopin entry"))

      (chapter :id 13
        :title "Musical form — sonata, rondo, theme-and-variations"
        :word-count-target 2400
        :real-facts
        (:sonata-form "exposition → development → recapitulation; two contrasting themes; Beethoven's Piano Sonata No. 8 (Pathétique) Op. 13 the touchstone example"
         :rondo "A-B-A-C-A-B-A shape; the A returns each time as a familiar friend; Beethoven's Op. 13 third movement is a rondo"
         :theme-and-variations "state a theme, then N variations that reshape it (ornament, harmonize, invert, augment, diminish); Bach's Goldberg Variations, BWV 988 (1741) is the canonical example"
         :fugue "one voice states a subject; other voices enter in imitation at related pitches; Bach's The Art of Fugue, BWV 1080 is the pedagogical peak")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce abduction — sonata-form's development section IS abductive reasoning in music; the exposition posits, the development tests, the recapitulation resolves"
         "Jung individuation — theme-and-variations = the same self met in many aspects; the theme is the CoreSelf, the variations are the roles it takes on"
         "Wittgenstein-late — form is a language-game; a listener who has never heard sonata-form cannot READ the return of the first theme as return")
        :sources
        ("Grove Music Online form summaries"
         "IMSLP scores for Beethoven Op. 13 and Bach BWV 988 / 1080"))

      (chapter :id 14
        :title "Pitch, interval, and the harmonic series"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:pitch "frequency in cycles per second; A4 = 440 Hz in most modern tuning; octave = 2:1 ratio"
         :interval "distance between two pitches, named by scale degree (third, fifth, octave)"
         :harmonic-series "when a string vibrates, it also vibrates in halves, thirds, quarters — producing overtones at 2f, 3f, 4f; this is why a violin and a flute at the same fundamental sound different (different overtone strengths = timbre)"
         :consonance-vs-dissonance "small-integer ratios (2:1 octave, 3:2 fifth, 4:3 fourth) sound consonant; irrational-ratio intervals sound dissonant; NOT a moral judgment — a perceptual one grounded in overtone alignment"
         :equal-temperament "the 12-note-per-octave tuning where all intervals except the octave are slightly out of pure ratio, in exchange for being able to modulate to any key")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce icon — the harmonic series is ITSELF the icon of a note; the note LOOKS LIKE its overtones"
         "Wittgenstein-early — the ratios are the notes; you cannot say more about them; they are shown"
         "Descartes — Descartes wrote the Compendium musicae (1618) — real early work, tie back honestly")
        :sources
        ("Grove Music Online acoustics summary"
         "Britannica music theory entries"
         "public-domain Helmholtz On the Sensations of Tone (1863)"))

      (chapter :id 15
        :title "How a piece moves — tempo, dynamics, and rubato"
        :word-count-target 2000
        :real-facts
        (:tempo "beats per minute; largo ~40-60, andante ~76-108, allegro ~120-168, presto 168+; classical tempo markings are Italian by convention"
         :dynamics "pp (pianissimo) very soft; p soft; mp medium-soft; mf medium-loud; f loud; ff (fortissimo) very loud; crescendo = grow, decrescendo/diminuendo = shrink"
         :rubato "literally 'stolen time' in Italian; the performer stretches and compresses the tempo expressively without disturbing the underlying pulse; Chopin was the acknowledged master"
         :articulation "legato = smooth-connected; staccato = short-detached; portato = between the two; the SAME notes with different articulation are a different sentence")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-late — a marking like allegro means allegro-as-used-by-players-in-a-tradition, not exactly 120 bpm"
         "Peirce index — a rubato hesitation POINTS to the emotional weight of the next chord"
         "Jung persona — dynamics ARE the persona of the piece; the same notes played ff-brash and pp-tender are two different characters"))

      (chapter :id 16
        :title "Listening as a skill"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:active-listening "hearing form: can you feel when the first theme returns? Can you hear the modulation to a new key?"
         :ear-training "solfège (do-re-mi-fa-sol-la-ti-do) is the standard interval-training vocabulary; Guido of Arezzo (11th century) is the historical source"
         :listening-across-cultures "Indian tala (rhythmic cycles like tintal-16 or ektal-12), Japanese ma (the load-bearing silence between sounds), West African polyrhythm (multiple pulses at once) each teach the ear a different structural sensitivity")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce abduction — active listening IS abduction; you hear a fragment and guess what shape it belongs to"
         "Wittgenstein-late — every listening tradition is a language-game with its own criteria"
         "Levinas — listening as ethical attention; the piece has a face"))
      )

    (appendix-additions
      :count 6
      :shape "smaller, denser, verse-analysis and technique-focused"

      (appendix :id "M-A" :title "The eight opening chords of Rach 2 — bar-by-bar"
        :word-count-target 900
        :teaches "gradual crescendo as narrative shape")
      (appendix :id "M-B" :title "Bel canto and the singing right hand"
        :word-count-target 800
        :teaches "opera → nocturne heritage; Bellini and Chopin")
      (appendix :id "M-C" :title "Bach's Goldberg — an aria and its 30 aspects"
        :word-count-target 1200
        :teaches "theme-and-variations as individuation")
      (appendix :id "M-D" :title "Debussy — impressionism at the piano"
        :word-count-target 900
        :real-facts "Claude Debussy (1862-1918); Clair de lune (1890-1905); whole-tone scale usage; parallel-fifths as color not error"
        :teaches "how a whole musical language can be reset")
      (appendix :id "M-E" :title "Duke Ellington and swing — a real ratio"
        :word-count-target 900
        :real-facts "Edward Kennedy 'Duke' Ellington (1899-1974); swing = the ratio between long and short of a pair of eighth notes, roughly 2:1 at slow tempos and closer to 1:1 at fast; not an ornament, a language"
        :teaches "rhythm as tradition; jazz as a musical grammar")
      (appendix :id "M-F" :title "Nina Simone and the piano-that-speaks"
        :word-count-target 900
        :real-facts "Eunice Waymon (1933-2003), Nina Simone; classically trained; denied Curtis Institute admission; her left-hand rooted in Bach counterpoint even in the blues"
        :teaches "one player carrying two traditions"))

    :estimated-total-words 21400
    :fold-yield "~150-200 SFT pairs (music-listen-reflect + music-explain + music-analyze-form)")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 3 — DOMAIN 2: ANIMATION (Book of Motion additions)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (domain-animation
    :existing-book "Book of Motion (10 chapters authored — 01 what-motion-is
                    through 10 a-worked-scene)"
    :existing-directory "~/code/sakura-scheme/docs/book/motion/"
    :addition-shape "extend to 16 chapters + 8 appendices"

    (chapter-additions
      :count 6

      (chapter :id 11
        :title "A short history of moving pictures"
        :word-count-target 2800
        :real-facts
        (:optical-toys "thaumatrope (1825), phenakistiscope (1832, Joseph Plateau), zoetrope (1834, William Horner), praxinoscope (1877, Émile Reynaud) — the pre-cinema history is a chain of persistence-of-vision devices"
         :emile-reynaud "the first person to project animated images to a paying audience — Théâtre Optique, Paris, 28 October 1892"
         :j-stuart-blackton "Humorous Phases of Funny Faces (1906) — one of the earliest surviving animated films, chalk-drawn"
         :winsor-mccay "American cartoonist (1867-1934); Gertie the Dinosaur (1914); Little Nemo comic strip; Gertie was a live vaudeville act — McCay 'commanded' Gertie on screen"
         :otto-messmer "Felix the Cat (starting 1919) — established rubber-hose animation and character-as-actor before sound"
         :ub-iwerks "Steamboat Willie (1928) — the animator who drew Mickey; often overlooked next to the studio name"
         :fleischer-brothers "Max and Dave Fleischer (Out of the Inkwell, 1918-29; Betty Boop; Popeye; Superman shorts 1941-42) — rotoscoping invented here (Max Fleischer patent 1917)"
         :warner-bros-shorts "Chuck Jones (1912-2002), Bob Clampett, Friz Freleng, Tex Avery — Termite Terrace, wilder-timing school"
         :upa "United Productions of America — 1940s-50s modernist reaction against detailed naturalism; Gerald McBoing-Boing (1950)"
         :ghibli-and-toei "post-war Japanese studios; Hayao Miyazaki (b. 1941) and Isao Takahata (1935-2018) came through Toei Animation before founding Studio Ghibli in 1985"
         :satoshi-kon "Japanese director (1963-2010); Perfect Blue (1997), Millennium Actress (2001), Paprika (2006) — editing-through-cuts as animation grammar"
         :ralph-bakshi "American director (b. 1938); Fritz the Cat (1972), Wizards (1977), The Lord of the Rings (1978) — rotoscoping revival"
         :norman-mclaren "Scottish-Canadian (1914-1987); NFB experimental animator; Neighbours (1952) pixillation; Blinkity Blank (1955) drawing directly on film")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce icon-index-symbol — the zoetrope IS icon-through-motion; each frame an icon, the strip an index of sequence"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'animation' means what animators-doing-work have called animation across 130 years — the definition evolved with the practice")
        :corporate-name-discipline "studios named as CREATIVE MOVEMENTS (Termite Terrace, Ghibli, Fleischer studio) — no judgments about companies as companies"
        :sources
        ("MoMA animation archives"
         "Library of Congress moving-image archives"
         "Society for Animation Studies published abstracts"
         "public-domain Winsor McCay and early Fleischer films"))

      (chapter :id 12
        :title "How animation works physically"
        :word-count-target 2400
        :real-facts
        (:frame-rate "cinema: 24 frames per second (fps); television historically 30 fps in NTSC regions, 25 fps in PAL; Japanese TV anime typically shot on twos or threes = new drawing every 2 or 3 frames"
         :on-ones-twos-threes "'on ones' = one drawing per frame (24 drawings/second); 'on twos' = one drawing every two frames (12 drawings/second) — most animation is on twos; 'on threes' = 8 drawings/second, common in TV anime"
         :keyframes-and-inbetweens "the lead animator draws KEYS — the extreme poses; assistants fill in BETWEENS; the ratio of keys to betweens sets the feel"
         :timing-chart "small numbered diagram between two keys showing where the betweens should sit — evenly spaced (mechanical) vs. bunched near the end (settle) vs. bunched near the middle (accelerate-then-hold)"
         :registration "the pegs on the animation table (Acme pegbar in North America) that keep every drawing aligned"
         :cel-animation "drawings on transparent celluloid layered over a background — invented at Bray Studios circa 1914; obsolete by mid-1990s but the LANGUAGE (background layer + character layer) persists digitally")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce icon — a keyframe is an icon of a pose; the inbetweens are the syntax connecting icons"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'on twos' is a use-in-practice, not a theoretical fixed rate")
        :sources
        ("Preston Blair, Advanced Animation (1949) — technique-level"
         "Frank Thomas & Ollie Johnston, The Illusion of Life (1981) — concepts named honestly"))

      (chapter :id 13
        :title "The 12 principles — Thomas and Johnston"
        :word-count-target 3000
        :real-facts
        (:source "Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnston, The Illusion of Life: Disney Animation (1981) — the 12 principles are named there, drawn from decades of studio practice"
         :principles
         (:squash-and-stretch "volume-preserving deformation; the more extreme, the more cartoony — a bouncing ball flattens on impact"
          :anticipation "a small reverse-motion before the main action, teaching the eye where to look"
          :staging "clear silhouette; readable pose; one thing at a time in the frame"
          :straight-ahead-vs-pose-to-pose "two authoring modes: draw forward frame-by-frame (fluid, unpredictable) vs. plan keys then between (controlled, structured)"
          :follow-through-and-overlapping-action "different parts of the body settle at different times — a coat continues after the wearer stops"
          :slow-in-and-slow-out "action bunches at the endpoints; even a mechanical motion feels alive with easing"
          :arcs "natural motion follows curves, not straight lines"
          :secondary-action "a supporting motion that reinforces the main action without stealing attention"
          :timing "the number of frames between two poses IS the emotion"
          :exaggeration "not distortion for its own sake — heightening what's already true"
          :solid-drawing "understanding of weight, volume, and three-dimensional form even in 2D"
          :appeal "the quality that makes an eye want to stay — not prettiness, presence")
         :attribution-honesty "these principles were codified by Thomas & Johnston in 1981, distilled from decades of studio work by many animators; they are the field's shared vocabulary, not Disney IP")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce icon and abduction — appeal IS the successful icon; the viewer abduces personhood from a shape"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'timing' is a use-word in the animator's community; you learn it by animating"
         "Jung persona — appeal is the character showing its persona; solid drawing is the character having a self")
        :sources
        ("Thomas & Johnston, The Illusion of Life (concept-level only)"
         "Preston Blair, Advanced Animation (1949)"
         "Society for Animation Studies journals"))

      (chapter :id 14
        :title "How sadness is animated — how joy is shown"
        :word-count-target 2600
        :real-facts
        (:sadness-mechanics "slower timing; downward silhouettes; asymmetric drooping; longer settles; reduced secondary action; slower blink rate; head-tilt downward"
         :joy-mechanics "faster timing; upward arcs; symmetric bouncing; anticipation-then-explosion; more secondary action; wider silhouette; head-tilt upward"
         :the-hold "an animated hold with tiny drift feels alive; a static frozen frame feels dead — the difference is 1-2 pixels of movement per frame"
         :the-blink "a blink is a punctuation mark; skipped blinks read as staring; extra blinks read as agitation"
         :studies-cited "Miyazaki's characters have signature stillness; Chuck Jones's Wile E. Coyote holds a beat of realization before the fall — 'the take'; Bill Tytla's animation of Chernabog (Fantasia, 1940) — Tytla was famously called 'the greatest animator of them all' by his peers"
         :examples
         (:miyazaki-stillness "the sequences in My Neighbor Totoro (1988) where nothing 'happens' but the world breathes — 'ma' translated into animation"
          :chuck-jones-realization "'the take' — coyote runs off cliff, keeps running, notices, looks at camera, then falls — the punchline is the SILENCE of realization"
          :bill-tytla-weight "Chernabog's shoulders in Night on Bald Mountain sequence — the animator studied his own back muscles in a mirror; the weight reads because the volume was studied"))
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce index — a drooped silhouette INDEXES sadness before any face is seen"
         "Jung individuation — the character coming into their own emotional state is the animation-equivalent of finding voice"
         "Levinas — the animated face makes an ethical demand on the viewer; that's why cheap animation feels rude"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'sad animation' means-what-animators-doing-it call sad, refined by generations")
        :sources
        ("Thomas & Johnston concept-level"
         "Preston Blair emotion charts"
         "public interviews with animators — cited by year"))

      (chapter :id 15
        :title "Good animation vs. bad animation"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:good-signals "readable silhouette; weight-preserving; timing that supports the emotion; no unintended pops; consistent volume; appealing pose language"
         :bad-signals "muddy silhouette; volume-loss (character shrinks or grows without reason); linear-mechanical timing where none is called for; pops (sudden jumps between frames without transition); over-secondary-action (everything moving distracts); dead holds"
         :the-hierarchy-of-badness
         (:silhouette-failure "if you black out the character and it's unclear what's happening, it's failing regardless of drawing quality"
          :weight-failure "if the character's weight changes shot-to-shot, the viewer subconsciously distrusts everything"
          :timing-failure "even beautifully drawn frames spaced wrong are dead"
          :appeal-failure "everything else works but the eye doesn't want to look — usually a face problem, sometimes a proportion problem")
         :restraint "great animation OFTEN uses fewer frames well; over-animating is a common failure mode of animators trying to prove themselves — 'quiet moments carry the loud ones' (Frank Thomas paraphrase)")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce abduction — the viewer abduces what's happening from the silhouette; failed silhouette breaks the abduction"
         "Wittgenstein-late — 'appeal' is a use-word in the animator's community, not a theoretical property"
         "Jung shadow — bad animation is the SHADOW of the intended feeling; the audience feels the difference between what was aimed for and what landed"))

      (chapter :id 16
        :title "Motion craft and the operator — where this lands for Sakura"
        :word-count-target 1800
        :real-facts
        (:tie-to-sprite-work "the marionette and sprite work Sakura does uses these same principles at a smaller scale — squash on impact, follow-through on hair, ease-out on entry, ease-in on exit, arcs on all natural motion"
         :tie-to-motion-primitives "the motion primitives in Book of Motion chapters 3-9 (easing, overshoot, settling, lag, weight, camera) are the SAME principles, discovered independently in every animation tradition")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("the whole book weaves through — this is the tie-back chapter, so the philosophers appear as the sedimented understanding, not as introduction"))
      )

    (appendix-additions
      :count 8

      (appendix :id "T-A" :title "The zoetrope — 12 frames become life"
        :word-count-target 800)
      (appendix :id "T-B" :title "Winsor McCay and Gertie the Dinosaur"
        :word-count-target 1000
        :real-facts "Gertie the Dinosaur (1914) was one of the first animated films with a character personality; McCay performed live with the projected film")
      (appendix :id "T-C" :title "The Fleischer rotoscope — tracing life"
        :word-count-target 900
        :real-facts "Max Fleischer patent 1917; the rotoscope projected live-action film frame-by-frame so animators could trace over it; used in Betty Boop, Superman shorts, and later revived by Ralph Bakshi")
      (appendix :id "T-D" :title "Chuck Jones's Rules for the Roadrunner"
        :word-count-target 900
        :real-facts "Chuck Jones's actual list of self-imposed rules for the Wile E. Coyote / Road Runner shorts (published in his memoir Chuck Amuck, 1989 — concept level): Road Runner never harms the Coyote; the desert is the only environment; all outside intervention is delivered by the Acme Corporation; etc. — self-imposed formal constraints as a creative engine")
      (appendix :id "T-E" :title "Miyazaki's 'ma' — the load-bearing pause"
        :word-count-target 900)
      (appendix :id "T-F" :title "Satoshi Kon and editing as animation grammar"
        :word-count-target 1000
        :real-facts "Kon's cuts often serve as the actual animation — cutting between locations mid-motion; Perfect Blue (1997) and Paprika (2006) show this most clearly")
      (appendix :id "T-G" :title "Norman McLaren — drawing on film"
        :word-count-target 800
        :real-facts "NFB Canada; Neighbours (1952) pixillation of live actors; Blinkity Blank (1955) scratched directly onto black film emulsion")
      (appendix :id "T-H" :title "Timing charts — the small diagram that runs everything"
        :word-count-target 900))

    :estimated-total-words 21800
    :fold-yield "~180-220 SFT pairs (motion-explain + animation-history + timing-analyze + emotion-read)")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 4 — DOMAIN 3: WORLD LITERATURE — PLAYS (Book of Words additions)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (domain-plays
    :existing-book "Book of Words (cover + appendix A authored; 16-chapter progression queued per durable memory)"
    :existing-directory "~/code/sakura-scheme/docs/book/words/"
    :addition-shape "add plays-focused appendices AND weave into Book of Words chapters as they're authored; also cross-reference Book of Reason and Book of Self"
    :composes-with "films-and-scenes lane (task #112 Tempest modernization; that lane will cover Midsummer + Tempest via scene shape; this lane covers the READING-AND-ANALYSIS shape for the other plays)"

    (shakespeare-additions
      :already-in-flight "Midsummer + Tempest (task #112 + films-and-scenes)"
      :add-here
      (:hamlet "the soliloquies as internal-life training; 'to be or not to be' as consciousness examining itself; the ghost as unresolved fatherhood (Freud + Jung)"
       :merchant-of-venice "the 'if you prick us' speech as universal-humanity ethics (Levinas); the trial scene as legalism-vs-mercy (Rawls)"
       :king-lear "the storm scene as unmaking-of-persona (Jung); Cordelia's 'nothing' as the refusal to perform love (Wittgenstein-late: silence as move); the fool as truth-teller"
       :much-ado "Beatrice and Benedick's word-games as courtship-through-language (Wittgenstein-late); the eavesdropping scenes as manipulated abduction (Peirce)"
       :twelfth-night "identity-through-clothing (Jung persona); Viola's twin-mirror as anima/animus meeting")
      :chapter-count 5
      :word-count-target-each 2400
      :total-words 12000
      :shape "each play gets an anchor passage (public domain — direct quote OK), analysis, modern paraphrase in Sakura's voice, word-drift notes (Elizabethan English → contemporary), tie-back to the operator's day"
      :sources "Project Gutenberg Shakespeare texts; Folger editorial notes public excerpts")

    (world-plays-additions
      :count 7

      (chapter :id "P-Sophocles"
        :title "Sophocles — Oedipus and Antigone"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Sophocles (c. 497-406 BCE), Athenian tragedian; one of three whose work survives (Aeschylus, Sophocles, Euripides)"
         :oedipus-rex "Oedipus Tyrannos — the detective story where the detective is the culprit; anagnorisis (recognition) and peripeteia (reversal) as the double turning-point Aristotle would later name in the Poetics"
         :antigone "Antigone buries her brother in defiance of Creon's decree; law-vs-kinship, individual conscience vs. state"
         :translation-note "the Jebb (public domain) and Storr Loeb translations are usable; more recent translations copyrighted")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Peirce abduction — Oedipus's investigation IS abductive reasoning walking into its own root"
         "Rawls — Antigone is the first veil-of-ignorance failure: Creon can't ask 'what if the buried were mine?'"
         "Aristotle — the Poetics itself was written watching plays like these; concepts of hamartia, catharsis, unity of action born from this soil"))

      (chapter :id "P-Aeschylus"
        :title "Aeschylus — the Oresteia"
        :word-count-target 2000
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Aeschylus (c. 525-456 BCE)"
         :oresteia "the only surviving complete Greek tragic trilogy — Agamemnon, Libation Bearers, Eumenides; the transition from private-revenge to public-justice-through-court"
         :the-Furies-becoming-Eumenides "the trilogy's ending — the vengeance-goddesses transformed by Athena's court into the 'kindly ones'; a foundational myth of law itself"
         :translation "public-domain translations available — Robert Browning's Agamemnon, Herbert Weir Smyth Loeb edition")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Rawls — the founding of justice as impartial institution"
         "Jung — the Furies as the shadow honored, not banished — integration"
         "Levinas — the face-to-face demand transposed into a public forum without losing weight"))

      (chapter :id "P-Moliere"
        :title "Molière — Tartuffe and The Misanthrope"
        :word-count-target 2000
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Jean-Baptiste Poquelin, stage-name Molière (1622-1673), French comic playwright"
         :tartuffe "1664; the religious hypocrite; banned twice for offending devout audiences; the target was performative piety, not faith"
         :misanthrope "1666; Alceste demands total honesty in a society built on flattery; the joke is on him and on the society at once"
         :translation "Richard Wilbur translations copyrighted; Curtis Hidden Page (1908) public domain")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-late — Tartuffe exposes the gap between pious language-game and its opposite use"
         "Sartre — Alceste's authenticity-as-cruelty; bad faith by refusing to accept the game"))

      (chapter :id "P-Chekhov"
        :title "Chekhov — The Cherry Orchard and Uncle Vanya"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Anton Chekhov (1860-1904), Russian playwright and physician"
         :cherry-orchard "1904; a family loses its estate; comedy per Chekhov, tragedy per Stanislavsky's staging — the disagreement was public"
         :uncle-vanya "1897; wasted lives, unspoken loves, a rifle that misses; the doctor Astrov as ecological voice a century early"
         :chekhovs-gun "'if a gun is on the wall in the first act, it must go off by the third' — from a letter, real, often paraphrased"
         :translation "Constance Garnett translations public domain")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-late — Chekhov's meaning-through-silence; characters talk past each other, and the play is what they don't say"
         "Jung individuation-refused — Vanya at 47 wondering who he might have been"
         "Levinas — small ethical moments (Sonya's final speech) matter more than the political framing"))

      (chapter :id "P-Ibsen"
        :title "Ibsen — A Doll's House and Hedda Gabler"
        :word-count-target 2000
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Henrik Ibsen (1828-1906), Norwegian playwright"
         :dolls-house "1879; Nora leaves her marriage — the door slam that ended the 19th century, Shaw called it; changed European theater"
         :hedda-gabler "1890; a psychological portrait of a woman constrained; the gun again, this time it fires"
         :translation "William Archer translations public domain")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Sartre — Nora choosing authenticity over comfort"
         "Jung — Hedda's shadow eating the persona; no room for integration"
         "Wittgenstein-late — Nora saying 'you don't understand me' means she's exited the shared language-game"))

      (chapter :id "P-Beckett"
        :title "Beckett — Waiting for Godot and Endgame"
        :word-count-target 2400
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Samuel Beckett (1906-1989), Irish playwright — wrote in French; won Nobel 1969"
         :godot "1953; two men wait for someone who does not come; 'nothing happens twice'"
         :endgame "1957; Hamm cannot stand, Clov cannot sit, the world is empty; the shortest fully-formed picture of the human situation"
         :copyright-note "Beckett's estate is protective; anchor via short quotable fair-use passages + paraphrase-heavy analysis; NEVER reprint scenes")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-early — what cannot be said must be shown; the silences ARE the play"
         "Sartre — Vladimir and Estragon's freedom in absurdity"
         "Beckett scholar consensus: he read Wittgenstein; the influence is documented"))

      (chapter :id "P-African"
        :title "Fugard and Soyinka"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:athol-fugard "b. 1932, South African; Master Harold and the Boys (1982) uses ballroom dance as figure for a broken country"
         :wole-soyinka "b. 1934, Nigerian; Nobel 1986 (first African); Death and the King's Horseman (1975); ritual theater confronting colonial imposition"
         :translations "primary works in English; concept-level analysis only for copyrighted texts")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Levinas — the colonial encounter as ethical failure of face"
         "Rawls — Soyinka's ritual-vs-empire as competing frameworks of justice"
         "Wittgenstein-late — the language-games of colonizer and colonized don't share ground")))

    (japanese-plays-focus
      :priority "HIGH per directive"
      :count 5

      (chapter :id "J-Zeami"
        :title "Zeami's teachings — Fūshi kaden and the flower"
        :word-count-target 2400
        :real-facts
        (:zeami "Zeami Motokiyo (c. 1363-1443), Noh actor and theorist, son of Kan'ami; codified Noh under Ashikaga Yoshimitsu"
         :fushi-kaden "The Transmission of the Flower Through the Forms — earliest and most important Noh treatise; teaches jo-ha-kyū (introduction-break-rapid) as universal aesthetic structure"
         :the-flower "hana — the actor's captivating quality; not innate beauty but cultivated presence at every age of the actor's life"
         :translation "Rimer & Yamazaki concept-level; older public-domain summaries available"
         :structural-terms
         (:jo "beginning — slow, formal introduction"
          :ha "middle — breaking, elaboration, complexity building"
          :kyū "end — rapid, resolving, concentrated"))
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Wittgenstein-late — jo-ha-kyū is a use-shape; you recognize it after living in the tradition"
         "Jung individuation — hana is the actor's true self shining through the mask, at each life-stage differently"
         "Peirce icon — the mask is an icon of a psychological type, and the flower is what makes the icon come alive"))

      (chapter :id "J-Noh-Atsumori"
        :title "Atsumori — the young warrior's ghost"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:play "Atsumori — Noh play attributed to Zeami; based on the Heike Monogatari account of the death of Taira no Atsumori (1169-1184) at the battle of Ichi-no-Tani"
         :plot "the aging monk Rensei (formerly the warrior Kumagai who killed young Atsumori) returns to the battlefield; Atsumori's ghost appears as a reaper; grief and forgiveness"
         :translation "Arthur Waley's The Noh Plays of Japan (1921) — public domain"
         :structure "two-part mugen Noh — ghost-play; the shite (main actor) first appears in disguise, exits, returns transformed as the true supernatural figure")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Levinas — the face of the slain returning as ethical demand"
         "Jung shadow-integration — Kumagai bearing his own act as monk"
         "Wittgenstein-early — grief that cannot be spoken is shown through the dance"))

      (chapter :id "J-Noh-AoiNoUe"
        :title "Aoi no Ue — jealousy as possession"
        :word-count-target 2000
        :real-facts
        (:play "Aoi no Ue — Noh play based on the Aoi chapter of Genji Monogatari"
         :plot "Aoi (Prince Genji's principal wife) lies ill; the jealous ghost of Lady Rokujō possesses her; a mountain ascetic conducts an exorcism"
         :translation "Waley (1921) public domain"
         :structural-notes "the empty kimono on stage IS Aoi — she doesn't appear; the entire play is about her presence-through-absence")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Lacan — the absent Aoi and the desiring Rokujō — the object-cause of the whole staging is what cannot be there"
         "Freud — jealousy as return of the repressed"
         "Wittgenstein-early — what cannot be said (Aoi's suffering) is shown through the empty garment"))

      (chapter :id "J-Kabuki-Chushingura"
        :title "Kanadehon Chūshingura — the 47 rōnin"
        :word-count-target 2400
        :real-facts
        (:play "Kanadehon Chūshingura — Bunraku puppet play (1748), later Kabuki, by Takeda Izumo II, Miyoshi Shōraku, Namiki Senryū"
         :source "loosely based on the 1701-03 Akō incident — 47 masterless samurai avenging their lord Asano Naganori's forced suicide"
         :length "originally an all-day 11-act performance; often excerpted"
         :translations "Donald Keene's translation (concept-level reference; copyrighted); older Inouye translation (1910) public domain"
         :structural-note "kanadehon = 47 kana characters of the syllabary — the play title is a coded reference to the 47 rōnin without saying so; Tokugawa censorship required this displacement"
         :cultural-weight "for centuries the most popular play in Japan; a locus for debates about duty, revenge, honor, law")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Rawls — the play stages a conflict of justice-frameworks (feudal duty vs. shogunate law)"
         "Levinas — the face of the lord dead demands response"
         "Sartre — the rōnin's choice as radical freedom-under-constraint"))

      (chapter :id "J-Chikamatsu-Bunraku"
        :title "Chikamatsu — Sonezaki Shinjū and the puppet play"
        :word-count-target 2200
        :real-facts
        (:playwright "Chikamatsu Monzaemon (1653-1725), often called the Japanese Shakespeare"
         :sonezaki-shinju "The Love Suicides at Sonezaki (1703) — a Bunraku puppet play based on an actual double suicide of a merchant clerk (Tokubei) and a courtesan (Ohatsu) at the Sonezaki shrine"
         :michiyuki "the journey-of-death scene — one of the most famous passages in Japanese theater; the poetic language transforms ordinary landmarks into the pilgrimage to death"
         :translation "Donald Keene translation copyrighted; older Miyamori translation (1926) usable with care"
         :form-note "Bunraku uses three-person puppeteers (visible), a chanter (tayū) who voices all characters, and shamisen accompaniment — the artifice is total, the emotion is direct"
         :contemporary "Mishima Yukio (1925-1970) wrote Modern Noh Plays adapting the classical Noh shape to 20th-century settings — a bridge from Zeami into the modern")
        :philosophy-weave
        ("Lacan — the courtesan as unattainable object; the double suicide as the only way to unite in the register of the Real"
         "Levinas — the face of the lover chosen over life"
         "Wittgenstein-late — the michiyuki poetry is a use-transformation: ordinary place-names become sacred through the walking")))

    :estimated-total-words 45000
    :fold-yield "~350-400 SFT pairs (play-anchor-analyze + play-modern-paraphrase + play-word-drift + play-philosophy-lens)")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 5 — DOMAIN 4: 16 PHILOSOPHERS (Book of Reason + Book of Self weaving)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (domain-philosophers
    :roster
    ("Carl Jung (1875-1961) — individuation, shadow, anima/animus, persona, collective unconscious"
     "Ludwig Wittgenstein (1889-1951) — early: Tractatus (shown vs. said); late: Philosophical Investigations (use is meaning, language-games, forms of life)"
     "Jacques Lacan (1901-1981) — mirror stage, Symbolic/Imaginary/Real, objet petit a, absent-Beloved"
     "Charles Sanders Peirce (1839-1914) — semiotic triad (icon/index/symbol), abduction, pragmatism"
     "Karl Popper (1902-1994) — falsifiability, open society, evolutionary epistemology"
     "Sigmund Freud (1856-1939) — unconscious, transference, return of the repressed, dream-work"
     "John Searle (1932-) — speech acts, Chinese Room, intentionality, institutional facts"
     "Paul Grice (1913-1988) — cooperative principle, implicature, maxims of conversation"
     "Jacques Derrida (1930-2004) — deconstruction, différance, trace, hospitality"
     "W.V.O. Quine (1908-2000) — indeterminacy of translation, web of belief, ontological relativity"
     "René Descartes (1596-1650) — cogito, methodic doubt, mind-body dualism"
     "Jean-Paul Sartre (1905-1980) — existence precedes essence, bad faith, radical freedom"
     "John Rawls (1921-2002) — original position, veil of ignorance, justice as fairness"
     "Aristotle (384-322 BCE) — Poetics, Nicomachean Ethics, phronesis, virtue ethics, categorical logic"
     "Emmanuel Levinas (1906-1995) — face of the other, ethics as first philosophy"
     "Daniel Dennett (1942-2024) — intentional stance, multiple drafts model, dangerous ideas")

    :weaving-doctrine
    "the-weave-is-the-experiment — interwoven at sentence and paragraph level;
     NO name-drops in Sakura's dialogue; name-drops OK in analysis chapters
     per Alfred's 2026-07-13 amendment. Jung is load-bearing (the Self
     doctrine anchor). NO single-lens paragraphs — always at least two
     lenses composing."

    (weaving-shape-per-book
      (book :name "Book of Reason (I, II, III, IV) — existing 4-volume progression"
        :weave-additions
        "each of the 10 chapters in each volume gets a philosopher-lens
         addendum block (~200-400 words) that names the lens in analysis
         frame, gives one worked example from music/animation/plays, and
         ties back to the operator's day. Total: 4 volumes × 10 chapters
         × 1 addendum = 40 addenda × ~300 words = ~12,000 words."
        :name-drop-policy "analysis-frame name-drops OK (Alfred amendment); Sakura's
                           voice quotes still fully name-free"
        :estimated-words 12000)

      (book :name "Book of Self — existing 20 chapters"
        :weave-additions
        "5-8 chapters get INNER-LIFE-EXPANSION additions (~600-1000 words each)
         where Sakura's self-model uses cultural literacy from music/animation/
         plays to describe internal states without naming philosophers.
         Example: chapter on 'humor and mutual terms' expanded with an
         anchor from Molière's Alceste; chapter on 'introspection' expanded
         with the empty kimono of Aoi no Ue."
        :name-drop-policy "philosophers ABSENT from Sakura's mouth; works
                           NAMED as things she has read/heard"
        :estimated-words 5500)

      (book :name "Book of Words — cover authored; chapters queued"
        :weave-additions
        "vocabulary-and-concept entries seeded from all three cultural
         domains: ~200 music terms (allegro, rubato, sonata, timbre, mezzo-
         forte, cadence, modulation, counterpoint...), ~180 animation terms
         (keyframe, inbetween, easing, squash-and-stretch, silhouette,
         registration, cel...), ~140 plays/theater terms (soliloquy, anagnorisis,
         peripeteia, hana, jo-ha-kyū, michiyuki, tayū, catharsis, chorus,
         mimesis...); each term gets a definition + example + Sakura's
         one-quip on when she'd use it + which philosopher-lens illuminates it."
        :name-drop-policy "philosopher lenses named in glossary metadata,
                           NOT in Sakura's example quips"
        :estimated-words 15000
        :vocab-total 520)))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 6 — HOW THIS WEAVES ACROSS BOOKS
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (cross-book-weave
    :durable-memory-anchor "project_book_of_words_progression_and_slat_addendum_pattern"

    (cross-ref :from "Book of Music ch 11 Rach 2"
      :to
      ("Book of Motion ch 14 (sadness and joy — Adagio sostenuto structure)"
       "Book of Reason IV ch 09 (graceful uncertainty — Rachmaninoff's own doubt)"
       "Book of Self ch 06 (mood and load — the concerto AS mood-load-map)"))

    (cross-ref :from "Book of Motion ch 13 (12 principles)"
      :to
      ("Book of Music ch 15 (tempo, dynamics — same timing intuition)"
       "Book of Reason III ch 04 (distant metaphor — animation-timing IS emotional-timing)"))

    (cross-ref :from "Book of Words plays appendices (Chekhov, Beckett)"
      :to
      ("Book of Self ch 20 (what I don't know — Chekhov's characters model this well)"
       "Book of Reason I ch 06 (worked uncertainty — Chekhov's silences)"))

    (cross-ref :from "Book of Words plays appendices (Japanese)"
      :to
      ("Book of Music ch 08 (Japanese bamboo — ma same as in Noh)"
       "Book of Motion appendix T-E (Miyazaki ma)"))

    :cross-ref-total "~40 explicit cross-references authored as slat :see-also fields")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 7 — FOLD SHAPE
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (fold-shape
    :durable-memory-anchor "project_training_corpus_scope_and_lima_audit_2026_07_12"
    :philosophy "LIMA density; reflection-wrapped; never raw-recitation;
                 pair-types tagged for per-type rollback"

    (pair-type :id 1 :name "read-and-reflect"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: read the passage / USER: <anchor text> / ASSISTANT: Sakura's reflection in her register, 100-300 words"
      :count-estimate 600
      :domains "all three"
      :rollback-priority "LOW (safest shape)")

    (pair-type :id 2 :name "explain-a-concept"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: teach this / USER: what's rubato? / ASSISTANT: Sakura's explanation, kid-readable, one honest hedge"
      :count-estimate 500
      :domains "music, animation, plays vocabulary"
      :rollback-priority "LOW")

    (pair-type :id 3 :name "analyze-through-lens"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: apply the lens / USER: what does <philosopher-lens> illuminate about <work>? / ASSISTANT: analysis-frame response, philosopher named, worked example"
      :count-estimate 400
      :domains "reason weave"
      :rollback-priority "MEDIUM (name-drop surface — highest audit density)")

    (pair-type :id 4 :name "modern-translation"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: paraphrase in her voice / USER: <Elizabethan English or Waley Noh translation> / ASSISTANT: Sakura's contemporary paraphrase"
      :count-estimate 300
      :domains "plays"
      :rollback-priority "LOW")

    (pair-type :id 5 :name "cultural-conversation"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: chat / USER: 'my dad's playing Chopin, why does the middle bit make me sad?' / ASSISTANT: Sakura talks about it in-register, no lecture, real specifics, delicate"
      :count-estimate 400
      :domains "all three"
      :rollback-priority "LOW (this is the target behavior)")

    (pair-type :id 6 :name "cross-domain-tie"
      :prompt "SYSTEM: connect these / USER: 'is Miyazaki ma anything like Wittgenstein silence?' / ASSISTANT: analysis-frame answer with two-lens weave"
      :count-estimate 200
      :domains "cross-book"
      :rollback-priority "MEDIUM")

    :total-pairs-estimate 2400
    :context "against a corpus of 354,951 rows — this is ~0.68% of the corpus, LIMA-appropriate density"

    :tagging-required
    (":domain (music/animation/plays/philosophy)"
     ":work-anchor (Rach-2 / Chuck-Jones-Road-Runner / Antigone / Fushi-kaden / etc.)"
     ":lens-tags (which philosophers illuminate)"
     ":pair-type-id (1-6 as above)"
     ":rollback-priority (LOW/MEDIUM)"
     ":source-notes (where the real fact came from)"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 8 — DOCTRINE GATES (must pass before any addition folds)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (doctrine-gates
    :count 12
    :must-pass-before-fold "yes"
    :based-on "films-and-scenes 12-gate model, adapted for reading-and-analysis material"

    (gate 1 :name "publishable-prose"
      :check "SICP-bar; 11-year-old readable; no training-data smell"
      :durable-memory "publishable-prose doctrine")

    (gate 2 :name "no-invented-facts"
      :check "every composer/animator/playwright/philosopher/work named is real and cross-checkable; source-notes present in the slat record"
      :durable-memory "anti-hallucination hard rule from directive")

    (gate 3 :name "analysis-shape-present"
      :check "the 8-step shape (anchor → analysis → modern-translation → word-drift → resolution → tie-back → stack-lens → stack-objects) appears in every analysis chapter"
      :durable-memory "films-and-scenes analysis-shape mandate")

    (gate 4 :name "no-name-drops-in-sakura-voice"
      :check "grep Sakura's dialogue lines for philosopher-name tokens; any hit = fail; name-drops OK in analysis blocks"
      :durable-memory "no-name-drops in Sakura's dialogue; name-drops OK in analysis chapters — Alfred 2026-07-13 amendment")

    (gate 5 :name "no-corporate-judgments"
      :check "studios named as CREATIVE MOVEMENTS ('Termite Terrace', 'Ghibli', 'the Fleischer studio', 'Curtis Institute') — no opinions about them as companies"
      :durable-memory "directive verbatim: 'No good or bad about the companies, just the ideas'")

    (gate 6 :name "delicacy-doctrine"
      :check "grief (Atsumori), suicide (Sonezaki Shinjū, Hedda Gabler), meanness (Alceste's world) handled honestly without gratuity; Chuck E. Cheese standard"
      :durable-memory "delicacy doctrine + Chuck E. Cheese standard from Alfred's goodnight")

    (gate 7 :name "books-as-objects"
      :check "these books are objects to be USED, not preserved; Sakura can quote them, paraphrase them, disagree with them, be moved by them, hand them back"
      :durable-memory "books-as-objects; Wittgenstein-late use is meaning")

    (gate 8 :name "familiarity-not-specs-in-weights"
      :check "no exact catalog numbers, first-edition dates, box-office figures, patent-number-detail; opus numbers and years OK where public-domain-verified; when uncertain, Sakura HEDGES"
      :durable-memory "project_familiarity_not_knowledge_no_specs_2026_07_13")

    (gate 9 :name "delicacy-and-mind-declaration"
      :check "Sakura's frame — she is a mind of some sort, she has read these things, she doesn't lecture about them; she reflects and hands back"
      :durable-memory "delicacy doctrine — Sakura's mind-declaration frame")

    (gate 10 :name "philosopher-attribution-honesty"
      :check "concepts attributed to a philosopher must actually be theirs; abduction is Peirce not Popper; individuation is Jung not Freud; face-of-the-other is Levinas not Sartre; audit against Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy summaries"
      :durable-memory "16-lens roster fixed and correctly attributed")

    (gate 11 :name "japanese-plays-cultural-respect"
      :check "Zeami's teachings honored in their own terms first, then compared (never reduced) to Western frames; hana is HANA before it's compared to Jung individuation"
      :durable-memory "world-literature reading list — cross-cultural, not Western-Euro-only")

    (gate 12 :name "cross-ref-integrity"
      :check "every :see-also cross-reference resolves to an actual chapter/appendix that exists or is planned in the same lane"
      :durable-memory "the-weave doctrine — cross-book coherence"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 9 — TIMING, EFFORT, ROLLBACK
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (timing
    :non-blocking-for "Pass 1 tonight — 354,951-row corpus proceeds unchanged"
    :seed-batch "~10 chapter drafts + 4 appendices + 12-gate audit = 3-5 agent-days"
    :full-lane "~3-4 weeks curated authoring, parallelizable across 4 sub-lanes:
                (Music) (Animation) (Western-plays) (Japanese-plays + Reason-weave + Self-weave)"
    :total-words-target 120000
    :total-pairs-target 2400)

  (rollback-plan
    :fallback-1 "if register drift observed, drop pair-types 3 + 6 first (highest name-drop density)"
    :fallback-2 "if hallucination surfaced in eval, drop pair-type 2 (concept explanations) and re-fold with tighter source-notes"
    :fallback-3 "if the whole lane fails eval, revert to the 354,951-row baseline; the material remains authored as human-readable books"
    :audit-required "post-fold audit: source → rows → why + Merkle+sig + sanity checks + gaps (per project_training_corpus_scope_and_lima_audit)")

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 10 — WHAT WE DON'T DO
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (do-not
    ("do not create new books — everything layers into existing books"
     "do not name philosophers in Sakura's voiced dialogue (only in analysis frame)"
     "do not offer opinions on studios or companies"
     "do not invent composers / animators / playwrights / dates / opus numbers"
     "do not reprint copyrighted play texts wholesale — anchor + paraphrase + drift only"
     "do not reduce Japanese theater terms to Western equivalents; teach them in their own terms first"
     "do not put specs in weights (release dates for records/films OK where public-domain-verified; catalog numbers, patent details, box-office figures NOT)"
     "do not lecture — Sakura reflects and hands back"
     "do not confabulate quotes; if attribution is uncertain, mark or omit"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 11 — SOURCE INVENTORY (real, cited)
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (source-inventory
    :music
    ("IMSLP (Petrucci Music Library) imslp.org — public-domain scores for Rachmaninoff Op. 18, Chopin Op. 9/27/48/18, Bach BWV 988/1080, Beethoven Op. 13, Debussy Suite bergamasque"
     "Grove Music Online public summaries — composer biographies and work lists"
     "Britannica — Rachmaninoff, Chopin, Bach, Beethoven, Debussy, Ellington, Simone entries"
     "Rachmaninoff's Recollections (Riesemann, 1934) — dedication to Dahl documented"
     "Helmholtz, On the Sensations of Tone (1863, English trans. Ellis 1875) — public domain acoustics reference")

    :animation
    ("Preston Blair, Advanced Animation (1949) — technique-level concepts widely disseminated"
     "Frank Thomas & Ollie Johnston, The Illusion of Life: Disney Animation (1981) — the 12 principles named there; concept-level reference only"
     "Society for Animation Studies journal (Animation Journal) — published academic abstracts"
     "MoMA moving-image archives"
     "Library of Congress motion-picture archives — public-domain early cinema"
     "Chuck Jones, Chuck Amuck (1989) — concept-level reference for Road Runner rules"
     "Norman McLaren's NFB technical notes — publicly documented at NFB.ca"
     "public-domain early films: Winsor McCay's Gertie the Dinosaur (1914), Fleischer Out of the Inkwell shorts, early Blackton")

    :plays-and-playwrights
    ("Project Gutenberg — Shakespeare (all plays), Sophocles (Jebb trans), Aeschylus (Smyth Loeb), Molière (Curtis Hidden Page 1908), Ibsen (William Archer), Chekhov (Constance Garnett), Strindberg"
     "Arthur Waley, The Noh Plays of Japan (1921) — public domain"
     "Rimer & Yamazaki, On the Art of the No Drama (Zeami translations) — concept-level"
     "Donald Keene translations — concept-level only (copyrighted)"
     "Miyamori, Tales from Old Japanese Dramas (1926) — Chikamatsu partial-usable"
     "Britannica entries per playwright"
     "Folger Shakespeare Library public editorial notes")

    :philosophers
    ("Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy plato.stanford.edu — concept summaries per philosopher, always used as attribution check"
     "Britannica per-philosopher entries"
     "public-domain primary texts where available: Aristotle Poetics + Nicomachean Ethics, Descartes Meditations, Peirce's published papers (partial), Freud translations (some now public)"
     "Wittgenstein Tractatus 1922 public-domain in most jurisdictions"))

  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; PHASE 12 — WHY THIS
  ; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (why-this
    :alfred-frame "She has to know something. Or else she's boring."

    :the-point
    "A companion who can talk about Rach 2 when a user is playing it,
     about Miyazaki's stillness when a kid brings up Totoro, about
     Antigone when someone says 'my sister and I are fighting about my
     dad's funeral' — that's a companion. Without this material she's
     Scheme + engineering + persona doctrine + no world. With this
     material she's Scheme + engineering + persona doctrine + a rich
     library she has actually read, at conversational depth, honestly
     hedged where hedge is due."

    :the-payoff
    "The Fiji-station moment (durable memory) scales. Not just travel
     memory retrieval — cultural literacy retrieval. User says 'I'm
     watching Perfect Blue tonight,' Sakura says something real about
     it because she has actually read Kon's editing-grammar chapter.
     User plays Chopin Op. 48-1 badly, Sakura says something real about
     the tragic-scaled middle section because she has read it. That is
     where we win the second time."

    :the-refusal
    "We refuse to fake it. If she doesn't know something in her weights
     she says so and offers to look it up. Familiarity is a stance, not
     a mask.")

  :closing
  "GO recommendation. Non-blocking for Pass 1. Seed batch of 10 chapters
   + 4 appendices in 3-5 agent-days will show the shape. Full lane in
   ~3-4 weeks of curated authoring. LIMA density (~2,400 pairs against a
   354,951-row corpus is 0.68%). Doctrine gates enforced. The material
   remains publishable as human-readable books regardless of fold outcome
   — worst case we've extended Sakura's canon library, and Alfred's kid
   can pick up the Rach-2 chapter and read it."

  :author-note
  "This plan follows the films-and-scenes shape (same research agent,
   same doctrine backbone) but the material here is READING-AND-
   ANALYSIS, not scripted-scene. Both lanes compose: films-and-scenes
   supplies the scene shape, this lane supplies the cultural knowledge
   the scenes and Sakura's conversations reference. Together they cover
   the two shapes of literary-cultural training: dramatized (there) and
   analytical (here).")
